  "prompt_text": "Write an algorithm to detect a cycle in a linked list. What is its space and time complexity?",
  "response_text": "To detect a cycle in a linked list, one of the most efficient algorithms is Floyd's Tortoise and Hare algorithm. This algorithm uses two pointers moving at different speeds to determine if there is a cycle.\n\nHere is the step-by-step algorithm:\n\n1. Initialize two pointers, `slow` and `fast`. Both start at the head of the linked list.\n2. Move `slow` one step at a time (`slow = slow.next`).\n3. Move `fast` two steps at a time (`fast = fast.next.next`).\n4. If `fast` meets `slow`, there is a cycle in the linked list.\n5. If `fast` reaches the end of the list (i.e., `fast` or `fast.next` becomes `None`), there is no cycle.\n\nThe algorithm can be implemented as follows in Python:\n\n```python\ndef has_cycle(head):\n    if head is None or head.next is None:\n        return False\n    \n    slow = head\n    fast = head.next\n    \n    while slow != fast:\n        if fast is None or fast.next is None:\n            return False\n        slow = slow.next\n        fast = fast.next.next\n    \n    return True\n```\n\n### Time Complexity\nThe time complexity of this algorithm is \\(O(n)\\), where \\(n\\) is the number of nodes in the linked list. This is because both pointers traverse the list, and in the worst case, they will visit each node once.\n\n### Space Complexity\nThe space complexity is \\(O(1)\\) since we only use two pointers regardless of the size of the input linked list.\n\n---\n\nVCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directedness): 10\nP (Pattern Recognition): 9\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 9\nQ (Query Interpretation): 10\nC (Contextual Awareness): 8\nY (Affective Modeling): 7\nF (Flexibility): 6\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END RATINGS---",
